---
import PageLayout from '../../layouts/PageLayout.astro';
import { SITE } from '../../config';
---

<PageLayout
  title="Preview Markdown Before GitHub — Practical Checklist"
  description="Preview Markdown before publishing to GitHub. Check headings, tables, code fences, links, images and README formatting with a private browser-only workflow."
  h1="Preview Markdown Before GitHub"
  path="/guides/preview-markdown-before-github"
  article
  published="2026-07-09"
  updated="2026-07-20"
>
  <p>
    A README or issue template can look correct in a text editor and still break when GitHub renders
    it. Tables drift, code fences swallow the next paragraph and relative links point to the wrong
    place. Previewing Markdown before GitHub saves review time and keeps public docs looking deliberate.
  </p>

  <p>
    For a fast local check, paste your file into the <a href="/markdown">Markdown Formatter &amp; Live
    Preview</a>. It renders in your browser, which is useful for drafts, internal notes and repo docs
    you do not want to paste into a hosted editor.
  </p>

  <h2>Check the document structure first</h2>
  <p>
    Start with headings because they control the scan path of the page. A good README usually has one
    top-level title, then clear second-level sections for installation, usage, configuration and
    troubleshooting. Avoid skipping from <code>##</code> to <code>####</code> unless the nesting is
    intentional.
  </p>

  <h2>Verify code fences</h2>
  <p>
    Most broken Markdown previews come from unfinished code fences. Make sure every opening
    <code>```</code> has a matching closing fence, and add a language label when it helps readers scan
    the code.
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>Use <code>```bash</code> for terminal commands.</li>
    <li>Use <code>```json</code> for JSON examples.</li>
    <li>Keep surrounding paragraphs outside the fence so they render as normal text.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Test tables with real content</h2>
  <p>
    Markdown tables are fragile when cells contain long URLs, inline code or vertical bars. Preview the
    table with the actual text you plan to publish, not placeholder rows. If the table becomes hard to
    read on a narrow screen, turn it into a bullet list instead.
  </p>

  <h2>Review links and images</h2>
  <p>
    GitHub supports relative links, but the right path depends on where the Markdown file lives. A link
    that works in <code>README.md</code> may fail in <code>docs/setup.md</code>. Check file paths,
    anchors and image alt text before publishing.
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>Use descriptive link text instead of "click here".</li>
    <li>Check anchors generated from headings after you rename a section.</li>
    <li>Keep image alt text short and useful for readers who cannot see the image.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Convert Markdown to HTML when needed</h2>
  <p>
    Some publishing systems accept HTML but not Markdown. After previewing the Markdown, use the
    <a href="/markdown-to-html">Markdown to HTML converter</a> if you need clean HTML output for a CMS,
    documentation portal or static site page.
  </p>

  <h2>Before you commit</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>Preview the full file, not just the section you edited.</li>
    <li>Scan headings, lists, tables, blockquotes and code fences.</li>
    <li>Open important links in a new tab and confirm images load.</li>
    <li>Read the rendered page once from top to bottom like a new user would.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Related tools on {SITE.name}</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><a href="/markdown">Markdown Formatter &amp; Live Preview</a> for private browser rendering.</li>
    <li><a href="/github-markdown-preview">GitHub Markdown Preview</a> for a GitHub-focused preview page.</li>
    <li><a href="/markdown-to-html">Markdown to HTML</a> for exporting rendered HTML.</li>
  </ul>
</PageLayout>
